{
    "publish_date": "2012-08-22T01:08:12.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT7M47S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "So you&#39;re me, and you&#39;re in math class.", 
            "dur": "1.907", 
            "start": "0.067"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And your teacher&#39;s ranting on and on", 
            "dur": "1.523", 
            "start": "1.974"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "about this article about whether", 
            "dur": "1.226", 
            "start": "3.497"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "algebra should be taught in school \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.225", 
            "start": "4.723"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as if he doesn&#39;t realize that what he&#39;s teaching", 
            "dur": "1.489", 
            "start": "5.948"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "isn&#39;t even algebra \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.172", 
            "start": "7.437"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which could have been interesting \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.124", 
            "start": "8.609"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but how to manipulate symbols", 
            "dur": "1.204", 
            "start": "9.733"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and some special cases of elementary algebra \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.788", 
            "start": "10.937"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which isn&#39;t.", 
            "dur": "1.209", 
            "start": "12.725"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And so, instead of learning about", 
            "dur": "1.707", 
            "start": "13.934"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "self-consistent systems and logical thought,", 
            "dur": "1.646", 
            "start": "15.641"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you spent all week memorizing", 
            "dur": "1.354", 
            "start": "17.287"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "how to graph parabolas.", 
            "dur": "1.554", 
            "start": "18.641"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "News flash: No one cares about parabolas.", 
            "dur": "3.463", 
            "start": "20.195"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which is why half the class is", 
            "dur": "1.221", 
            "start": "23.658"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "playing Angry Birds under their desks.", 
            "dur": "1.792", 
            "start": "24.879"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But, since you don&#39;t have a smart phone yet,", 
            "dur": "1.719", 
            "start": "26.671"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you have to resort to a more noble", 
            "dur": "1.301", 
            "start": "28.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and outdated form of boredom relief \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.932", 
            "start": "29.691"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that is, doodling.", 
            "dur": "1.646", 
            "start": "31.623"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you&#39;ve invented a game of your own.", 
            "dur": "1.796", 
            "start": "33.269"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A doodle game that connects the dots", 
            "dur": "1.996", 
            "start": "35.065"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in ways your math curriculum never will \u2013", 
            "dur": "2.462", 
            "start": "37.061"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "except instead of connecting to the closest dots", 
            "dur": "2.116", 
            "start": "39.523"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to discover the mysterious hidden picture", 
            "dur": "2.199", 
            "start": "41.639"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;ve got this precise method of skipping over", 
            "dur": "2.488", 
            "start": "43.838"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "some number of dots and connecting them that way.", 
            "dur": "1.937", 
            "start": "46.326"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In the past you&#39;ve characterized how this works", 
            "dur": "1.898", 
            "start": "48.263"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "if your dots are arranged in a circle \u2013 say 11 dots \u2013", 
            "dur": "2.751", 
            "start": "50.161"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and connect one to the dot four dots over,", 
            "dur": "2.154", 
            "start": "52.912"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get these awesome stars.", 
            "dur": "1.52", 
            "start": "55.066"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you can either draw the lines", 
            "dur": "1.193", 
            "start": "56.586"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the order of the dots,", 
            "dur": "1.148", 
            "start": "57.779"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or you can just keep going around and", 
            "dur": "1.427", 
            "start": "58.927"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "maybe it will hit all the dots, or maybe it won&#39;t,", 
            "dur": "2.152", 
            "start": "60.354"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "depending on how many dots are in your circle,", 
            "dur": "1.703", 
            "start": "62.506"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and how many dots you skip.", 
            "dur": "1.144", 
            "start": "64.209"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But then there are other shapes.", 
            "dur": "1.66", 
            "start": "65.353"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Circles are good friends with sine waves.", 
            "dur": "2.119", 
            "start": "67.013"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And sine waves are good friends with square waves.", 
            "dur": "2.305", 
            "start": "69.132"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And let&#39;s admit it, that&#39;s pretty cool looking.", 
            "dur": "1.951", 
            "start": "71.437"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, just two simple straight lines of dots", 
            "dur": "2.415", 
            "start": "73.388"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "connecting the dots from one line to the other", 
            "dur": "2.245", 
            "start": "75.803"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in order somehow gives you", 
            "dur": "1.922", 
            "start": "78.048"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "this awesome woven curve shape.", 
            "dur": "2.077", 
            "start": "79.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Another student is asking the teacher when he&#39;s ever", 
            "dur": "2.156", 
            "start": "82.047"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "going to need to know how to graph a parabola \u2013", 
            "dur": "1.873", 
            "start": "84.203"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even as he hides his multi-million dollar enterprise", 
            "dur": "2.664", 
            "start": "86.076"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of a parabola graphing game under his desk.", 
            "dur": "2.883", 
            "start": "88.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If your teacher thought about it,", 
            "dur": "1.277", 
            "start": "91.623"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "he would probably think shooting birds at things", 
            "dur": "2.182", 
            "start": "92.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is a great reason to learn about parabolas", 
            "dur": "1.948", 
            "start": "95.082"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because he&#39;s come to understand that", 
            "dur": "1.579", 
            "start": "97.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "education is about money and prestige and", 
            "dur": "1.459", 
            "start": "98.609"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "not about becoming a better human able to do great things.", 
            "dur": "2.86", 
            "start": "100.068"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You yourself haven&#39;t done anything really great yet", 
            "dur": "2.021", 
            "start": "102.928"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but you figure the path to your future greatness", 
            "dur": "2.078", 
            "start": "104.949"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "lies more in inventing awesome new connect-the-dot arrangements", 
            "dur": "2.94", 
            "start": "107.027"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "than in graphing parabolas or shooting birds at things.", 
            "dur": "2.645", 
            "start": "109.967"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And that&#39;s when you begin to worry.", 
            "dur": "1.721", 
            "start": "112.612"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "What if this cool liney curvey thing you drew", 
            "dur": "2.488", 
            "start": "114.333"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "approximates a parabola?", 
            "dur": "2.243", 
            "start": "116.821"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "As if your teacher doesn&#39;t realize", 
            "dur": "1.778", 
            "start": "119.064"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "everyone has their phones under their desks,", 
            "dur": "1.497", 
            "start": "120.842"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but he&#39;s underpaid and overworked and", 
            "dur": "1.404", 
            "start": "122.339"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "his whole word runs on plausible deniability,", 
            "dur": "2.135", 
            "start": "123.743"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so he shouts state-mandated, pass the test,", 
            "dur": "2.366", 
            "start": "125.878"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "teach-to-the-middle nonsense at students", 
            "dur": "1.626", 
            "start": "128.244"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "who are not at all fooled", 
            "dur": "1.239", 
            "start": "129.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by his false enthusiasm or false mathematics and", 
            "dur": "2.329", 
            "start": "131.109"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "he pretends he&#39;s teaching algebra and", 
            "dur": "1.144", 
            "start": "133.438"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the students pretend to be taught algebra and", 
            "dur": "1.859", 
            "start": "134.582"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "everyone else involved in the system", 
            "dur": "1.527", 
            "start": "136.441"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is too invested to do anything", 
            "dur": "1.117", 
            "start": "137.968"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but pretend to believe them both.", 
            "dur": "1.483", 
            "start": "139.085"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You think maybe it&#39;s a hyperbola,", 
            "dur": "1.985", 
            "start": "140.568"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is similar to the parabola", 
            "dur": "1.579", 
            "start": "142.553"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in that they are both conic sections.", 
            "dur": "1.761", 
            "start": "144.132"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A hyperbola is a nice vertical slice of cone,", 
            "dur": "2.663", 
            "start": "145.893"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the cone itself being just like a line swirled around in a circle,", 
            "dur": "2.94", 
            "start": "148.556"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is why the cone is like two cones radiating both ways;", 
            "dur": "3.258", 
            "start": "151.496"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the lovely hyperbola insecting both parts.", 
            "dur": "2.503", 
            "start": "154.754"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Two perfect curves, looking disconnected when seen alone", 
            "dur": "3.06", 
            "start": "157.257"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but sharing their common conic heritage.", 
            "dur": "2.413", 
            "start": "160.317"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "While the boring old parabola is a slice taken at an angle", 
            "dur": "2.982", 
            "start": "162.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "completely meant to miss the top part of the cone and", 
            "dur": "2.133", 
            "start": "165.712"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to miss wrapping around the bottom like an ellipse would.", 
            "dur": "2.832", 
            "start": "167.845"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it&#39;s such a special, specific case of conic section", 
            "dur": "2.447", 
            "start": "170.677"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that all parabolas are exactly the same,", 
            "dur": "1.781", 
            "start": "173.124"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "just bigger or smaller or moved around.", 
            "dur": "2.242", 
            "start": "174.905"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Your teacher could just as well hand you parabolas already drawn", 
            "dur": "3.139", 
            "start": "177.147"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and have you draw coordinate grids on parabolas", 
            "dur": "2.019", 
            "start": "180.286"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "rather than parabolas on coordinate grids.", 
            "dur": "1.886", 
            "start": "182.305"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it&#39;s stupid, and you hate it,", 
            "dur": "2.088", 
            "start": "184.191"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and you don&#39;t wanna learn to graph them,", 
            "dur": "1.243", 
            "start": "186.279"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even if it means not making a billion dollars", 
            "dur": "1.737", 
            "start": "187.522"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "from a game about shooting birds at things.", 
            "dur": "2.662", 
            "start": "189.259"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Meanwhile anyone who actually learns how to think mathematically", 
            "dur": "2.79", 
            "start": "191.921"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "can then learn to graph a parabola or anything else", 
            "dur": "2.553", 
            "start": "194.711"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they need in like five minutes.", 
            "dur": "1.543", 
            "start": "197.264"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But teaching how to think is an individualized process", 
            "dur": "2.785", 
            "start": "198.807"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that gives power and responsibility to individuals", 
            "dur": "2.119", 
            "start": "201.592"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while teaching what to think can be done", 
            "dur": "1.676", 
            "start": "203.711"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with one-size-fits-all bullet points and check-boxes", 
            "dur": "2.338", 
            "start": "205.387"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and our culture of excuses demands that we do the latter,", 
            "dur": "2.944", 
            "start": "207.725"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "keeping ourselves placated in the comforting structure", 
            "dur": "2.097", 
            "start": "210.669"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of tautology and clear expectations.", 
            "dur": "1.964", 
            "start": "212.766"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Algebra has become a check-box subject and", 
            "dur": "2.485", 
            "start": "214.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "mathematics weeps alone in the top of the ivory tower prison", 
            "dur": "3.08", 
            "start": "217.215"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to which she has been condemned.", 
            "dur": "2.246", 
            "start": "220.295"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But you&#39;re not interested in check-boxes;", 
            "dur": "1.731", 
            "start": "222.541"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;re interested in dots, and lines that connect them.", 
            "dur": "2.449", 
            "start": "224.272"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe you could connect them with semicircles,", 
            "dur": "1.857", 
            "start": "226.721"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to give visual structure to lines that would otherwise overlap.", 
            "dur": "2.74", 
            "start": "228.578"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you could say one dot is the center of a circle and", 
            "dur": "2.536", 
            "start": "231.318"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "another defines a radius and draw the entire circle", 
            "dur": "2.51", 
            "start": "233.854"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and do things that way.", 
            "dur": "1.406", 
            "start": "236.364"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You could make rules about how every dot", 
            "dur": "1.841", 
            "start": "237.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is the center of a circle with its neighbor being the radius,", 
            "dur": "2.146", 
            "start": "239.611"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or say one dot stays the center of all circles,", 
            "dur": "2.691", 
            "start": "241.757"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and all of the others define radii.", 
            "dur": "2.184", 
            "start": "244.448"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But then you just get concentric circles,", 
            "dur": "1.757", 
            "start": "246.632"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which I suppose should have been obvious.", 
            "dur": "1.556", 
            "start": "248.389"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But what if you did it the other way around and", 
            "dur": "1.828", 
            "start": "249.945"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "said one dot always stays on the circle and", 
            "dur": "2.261", 
            "start": "251.773"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "all the other dots are centers, like this.", 
            "dur": "2.283", 
            "start": "254.034"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Looks more promising.", 
            "dur": "1.363", 
            "start": "256.317"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you try putting all the dots in a circle and", 
            "dur": "1.723", 
            "start": "257.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "using them as circle centers and", 
            "dur": "1.557", 
            "start": "259.403"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "choose just one dot for the circles to go through and", 
            "dur": "2.448", 
            "start": "260.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get this awesome shape that looks kind of like a heart.", 
            "dur": "2.806", 
            "start": "263.408"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So let&#39;s call it, oh I don&#39;t know, a cardioid.", 
            "dur": "2.29", 
            "start": "266.214"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which happens to be the same curve that you get", 
            "dur": "1.687", 
            "start": "268.504"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when parallel lines like rays of light reflect off a circle", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "270.191"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the same heart of sunshine in a cup.", 
            "dur": "2.492", 
            "start": "273.331"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe instead of circle centers", 
            "dur": "1.322", 
            "start": "275.823"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you could have points all on the curve of a circle,", 
            "dur": "2.292", 
            "start": "277.145"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which means you need three points to define a circle,", 
            "dur": "2.736", 
            "start": "279.437"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "maybe just a point and its two closest neighbors to start with.", 
            "dur": "3.231", 
            "start": "282.173"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And of course, any collection of circles is two-colorable,", 
            "dur": "3.172", 
            "start": "285.404"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which means you can contrast light and dark colors", 
            "dur": "2.084", 
            "start": "288.576"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "for a classy color scheme.", 
            "dur": "1.115", 
            "start": "290.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe you could throw down some random points", 
            "dur": "1.953", 
            "start": "291.775"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to make all possible circles.", 
            "dur": "1.223", 
            "start": "293.728"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Only that would be a lot of circles,", 
            "dur": "1.393", 
            "start": "294.951"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so you choose just ones you like.", 
            "dur": "1.364", 
            "start": "296.344"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And then, against your will, you begin to wonder", 
            "dur": "1.775", 
            "start": "297.708"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "how many points it takes to define the boring old parabola.", 
            "dur": "2.912", 
            "start": "299.483"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Because parabolas are actually a lot like circles in that", 
            "dur": "2.183", 
            "start": "302.395"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "both are like extreme ellipses,", 
            "dur": "2.274", 
            "start": "304.578"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because a circle is like taking one focus of an ellipse", 
            "dur": "3.112", 
            "start": "306.852"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and putting the other focus zero distance away.", 
            "dur": "1.888", 
            "start": "309.964"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And a parabola is like an ellipse where", 
            "dur": "2.447", 
            "start": "311.852"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "one focus is infinity distance away.", 
            "dur": "1.874", 
            "start": "314.299"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which is why everyone lies to you and says", 
            "dur": "1.836", 
            "start": "316.173"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "throwing balls or shooting birds is all about parabolas", 
            "dur": "2.477", 
            "start": "318.009"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when really it&#39;s about ellipses", 
            "dur": "1.781", 
            "start": "320.486"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because the earth is a sphere and", 
            "dur": "1.779", 
            "start": "322.267"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "gravity doesn&#39;t actually go straight down.", 
            "dur": "1.733", 
            "start": "324.046"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And the other focus of the elliptical orbit of", 
            "dur": "1.968", 
            "start": "325.779"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "your thrown object of choice may be very far away,", 
            "dur": "2.476", 
            "start": "327.747"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but very far away is a great bit closer than infinity.", 
            "dur": "3.294", 
            "start": "330.223"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So let&#39;s not fool ourselves.", 
            "dur": "1.333", 
            "start": "333.517"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can&#39;t look at everything that seems kind of parabolic", 
            "dur": "3.051", 
            "start": "334.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and call it a parabola.", 
            "dur": "1.3", 
            "start": "337.901"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Sure, if you connect two dots with a hanging string or chain,", 
            "dur": "2.507", 
            "start": "339.201"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it looks parabolic, and so do structurally strong arches,", 
            "dur": "2.834", 
            "start": "341.708"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but they&#39;re actually catenary arches and", 
            "dur": "1.396", 
            "start": "344.542"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "maybe you can&#39;t tell by sight,", 
            "dur": "1.47", 
            "start": "345.938"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but if you&#39;re an architect you&#39;d better know the difference.", 
            "dur": "2.1", 
            "start": "347.408"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Though caternarys are quite related to parabolas,", 
            "dur": "1.611", 
            "start": "349.508"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get them by rolling around a parabola", 
            "dur": "1.56", 
            "start": "351.119"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and tracing the focus", 
            "dur": "1.068", 
            "start": "352.679"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which makes them a cousin of the ellipse and", 
            "dur": "1.404", 
            "start": "353.747"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even a hyperbola is like an ellipse that got turned inside out", 
            "dur": "2.284", 
            "start": "355.151"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or whose focus went through infinity and", 
            "dur": "1.67", 
            "start": "357.435"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "came out the other side or something.", 
            "dur": "1.807", 
            "start": "359.105"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And of course parabolas and hyperbolas and ellipses", 
            "dur": "1.494", 
            "start": "360.912"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are all conic sections which mean", 
            "dur": "1.675", 
            "start": "362.406"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they all come from a line that got spun around.", 
            "dur": "1.851", 
            "start": "364.081"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And a line is just what happens", 
            "dur": "1.121", 
            "start": "365.932"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when a couple dots get connected.", 
            "dur": "1.222", 
            "start": "367.053"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe what happens when your circle is so big that,", 
            "dur": "2.403", 
            "start": "368.275"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like the extreme ellipse that becomes a parabola,", 
            "dur": "3.137", 
            "start": "370.678"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the extreme circle is broken at infinity and", 
            "dur": "2.248", 
            "start": "373.815"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "becomes a line before getting larger than infinitely big", 
            "dur": "2.981", 
            "start": "376.063"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which brings it back to the other side.", 
            "dur": "1.594", 
            "start": "379.044"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This linear circle, the infinite in-between.", 
            "dur": "2.692", 
            "start": "380.638"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe a line is what happens", 
            "dur": "1.753", 
            "start": "383.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when you roll around a circle and trace the focus.", 
            "dur": "2.009", 
            "start": "385.083"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or rather the 2 foci, which are zero distance apart, in ellipse terms.", 
            "dur": "3.638", 
            "start": "387.092"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which makes you wonder what you get", 
            "dur": "1.55", 
            "start": "390.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when you roll around an ellipse and trace the foci.", 
            "dur": "2.412", 
            "start": "392.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, there&#39;s lots of great shapes", 
            "dur": "1.809", 
            "start": "394.692"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you can get by rolling around shapes on other shapes,", 
            "dur": "2.116", 
            "start": "396.501"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like if you roll a circle around a circle and trace the focus,", 
            "dur": "2.799", 
            "start": "398.617"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get just another circle.", 
            "dur": "1.432", 
            "start": "401.416"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But, if you trace a point on the edge,", 
            "dur": "1.748", 
            "start": "402.848"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get our awesome friend the cardioid again.", 
            "dur": "2.302", 
            "start": "404.596"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So now it&#39;s related to circles in three ways ,", 
            "dur": "2.311", 
            "start": "406.898"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which means it&#39;s a close cousin of the ellipse", 
            "dur": "2.117", 
            "start": "409.209"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and a second cousin to the infinite ellipse or, parabola.", 
            "dur": "2.56", 
            "start": "411.326"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Except, not just that, if you take a parabola and", 
            "dur": "2.216", 
            "start": "413.886"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "invert it around the unit circle, reversing inside and outside,", 
            "dur": "1.529", 
            "start": "416.102"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "one half becomes two, one hundred becomes a hundredth,", 
            "dur": "4.141", 
            "start": "417.631"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "one stays one, infinity becomes zero,", 
            "dur": "2.046", 
            "start": "421.772"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you get once again, the cardioid.", 
            "dur": "3.126", 
            "start": "423.818"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The cardioid is the anti-parabola which is good", 
            "dur": "2.755", 
            "start": "426.944"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because parabolas make you sad but you heart cardioids.", 
            "dur": "3.123", 
            "start": "429.699"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And of course, any time you want to", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "432.822"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "connect two dots on a piece of paper,", 
            "dur": "1.774", 
            "start": "434.242"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "instead of drawing the line you could fold the line.", 
            "dur": "2.644", 
            "start": "436.016"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Here&#39;s the thing about connecting dots.", 
            "dur": "1.886", 
            "start": "438.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can have all the steps laid out for you,", 
            "dur": "1.997", 
            "start": "440.546"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "taking whatever next step is easiest and closest", 
            "dur": "2.955", 
            "start": "442.543"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and be sure of what you&#39;re getting the whole time.", 
            "dur": "2.271", 
            "start": "445.498"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This way is safe and comfortable.", 
            "dur": "2.199", 
            "start": "447.769"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or, you can try new ways of connecting dots", 
            "dur": "2.177", 
            "start": "449.968"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and not know what you&#39;re going to get.", 
            "dur": "1.498", 
            "start": "452.145"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Maybe it will be something great, maybe it will fail.", 
            "dur": "2.787", 
            "start": "453.643"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And when it fails it will be your fault.", 
            "dur": "1.749", 
            "start": "456.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can&#39;t blame anyone else, not mathematics", 
            "dur": "2.316", 
            "start": "458.179"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or the system or the check-boxes.", 
            "dur": "1.488", 
            "start": "460.495"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But if I am to have faults I would rather they be my own.", 
            "dur": "3.972", 
            "start": "461.983"
        }
    ], 
